snippet.textDisplay:
The only tips I would give you for next time is to make the masa a little thinner like a thick paste so it spreads easier on the corn husk so that the filling can sit in the middle

When you put them in the pot put them in facing up in like pyramid formation and cover them with a few more leaves to steam that way there is less risk of losing any filling...then weigh down the lid with something

Also if you are making a lot put a fork in the water so if it runs out it makes noise and you can add more so they don't burn (learned this the hard way)

Other than that you did amazing for your first time, especially since we don't measure anything, but I hope this experience gives you more confidence to try again because even if you felt something was off, jenna seemed to really like them so you're clearly doing something right

snippet.textDisplay: Tamales are made different depending  on the country, it is not necessarily from Mexico. It is a Latin American dish and varies from one country to another. For example, in Costa Rica we use plantain leafs and the traditional ingredients are sweet peppers, plum, pork or chicken, carrots, olives, among other things and we boiled them, we don't steamed them. I love this kind of videos because you represent many cultures.❤️🇨🇷

snippet.textDisplay: The masa should be spread very thinly over the entire husk except the very bottom portion. Then you add your filling and fold it “like a book”. This way the filling is wrapped in the masa. I hope that makes sense. You need very little filling and masa. People tend to overestimate the amount that goes into a tamal. I hope that helps!
snippet.textOriginal: The masa should be spread very thinly over the entire husk except the very bottom portion. Then you add your filling and fold it “like a book”. This way the filling is wrapped in the masa. I hope that makes sense. You need very little filling and masa. People tend to overestimate the amount that goes into a tamal. I hope that helps!

snippet.textDisplay: Hey Julien I’m quite impressed at your first attempt! For future reference, traditionally the lard is first whipped with a mixer and then added into the masa to make it fluffy. Instead of melting down the butter and oil, I recommend whipping them for a few minutes and then adding them in with your hands to the masa. :)

snippet.textDisplay: 18:07 it’s really not because what my family and I do every year is we go to Mexico and get chili from my great tios ranch and get pork and also the masa from him to and we go back to New Mexico (my state) and make the chili meat at like 7 am maybe and you have to make it hot like super spicy because they’re not gonna be as good if they’re not, and around 1 pm we start soaking the hoja and by like 2 pm we start spreading the masa with spoons because real authentic masa from Mexico is real messy and me and my grandpa set up the olla outside and start steaming them but not smoking them because than you’ll taste the smoke in the masa and than we stop making them when we have about 300 dozens of tamales and give them to family and friends and eat them all year because they’re really good

snippet.textDisplay: You did great!! Honestly, the only tip I have is how you put in the masa on the husk. You typically spread it out all the way across, to about 3/4 of the way to the top, place your filling, and then fold the sides in. This way the filling is surrounded by masa. My family does fold in the top as well, but never the bottom. We place them top down in the pot so nothing comes out. Good job! I’m proud of you!

snippet.textDisplay: For better tasting refried beans on the quick....do the whole pinto beans (not refried) and empty the whole can with the juice over oil.  let them come up to a boil so that they soften up and mash them.  add some salt (I also add cheese).  Tastes better than teh canned refried beans.  I find the refried has a metallic tastes.  Obviously best best tasting would be to boil the bean from scratch!
